## 📋 AWS Pentesting Checklist

- [ ] Find exposed S3 buckets (public listing/read/write)
- [ ] Check EC2 metadata endpoint (SSRF)
- [ ] Enumerate IAM permissions with stolen creds
- [ ] Check for privilege escalation paths
- [ ] Look for secrets in Lambda env vars
- [ ] Check SSM Parameter Store and Secrets Manager
- [ ] Audit security groups for open ports
- [ ] Check CloudTrail for logging gaps
- [ ] Look for public RDS snapshots
- [ ] Check unencrypted EBS volumes
- [ ] Test for exposed EKS/ECS services
- [ ] Look for hardcoded AWS keys in repos

---

## 🧠 Tips

- **Pacu** is the best tool for AWS exploitation
- Always check **IMDSv1** first — many old EC2s still use it
- **enumerate-iam** helps when you don't know your permissions
- Look for AWS keys in **GitHub, .env files, JS files**
- **Confused deputy attacks** via cross-account roles
- SNS/SQS misconfigurations can leak data

